---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { meta } from '../../data/snapshot';

// Scenario grid — intensive margin. Excess cost = base × exposed fraction × premium.
const scenarios = [
  { name: 'Low', base: '$20B', frac: '75%', exposed: '$15B', prem: '80bp', cost: '~$0.12B' },
  { name: 'Central', base: '$83B', frac: '~48%', exposed: '~$40B', prem: '90bp', cost: '~$0.36B' },
  { name: 'High', base: '$200B', frac: '30%', exposed: '$60B', prem: '110bp', cost: '~$0.66B' },
];
---
<Base
  title="The Cost of an Unfinancialized Compute Market · CCIR Research"
  description="A working estimate of what the compute market pays in excess cost of funds for having no way to hedge and trade compute forwards — the price of not being financialized. Hypothetical."
  ogImage="/og/home.png"
  showTape={false}
>
  <section class="wrap top">
    <header class="page-head">
      <div class="kicker">Research · Market Structure · {meta.as_of_date}</div>
      <h1>The Cost of an Unfinancialized Compute Market</h1>
      <p class="standfirst">
        A working estimate of what the compute market pays, in excess cost of
        funds, for having no way to hedge and trade compute forwards — the price
        of not being financialized.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="body">
      <h2>The question</h2>
      <p>
        If a liquid, low-basis, cleared compute-forward curve existed, GPU and
        AI-compute borrowers could sell forward the cash-flow-certainty
        component of their revenue and finance on contracted rather than
        uncontracted terms. This estimates the annual excess cost of funds the
        sector bears today for the <em>absence</em> of that market.
      </p>

      <h2>The lever, precisely</h2>
      <p>
        The peer-reviewed power-project-finance literature separates two things
        an offtake contract bundles: <strong>counterparty credit</strong> (will
        the customer pay) and <strong>cash-flow certainty</strong> (is the
        revenue locked). A price hedge buys only the second.
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.eneco.2022.106312" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Gohdes,
        Simshauser &amp; Wilson (<em>Energy Economics</em>, 2022)</a> isolate it: a fully-contracted
        plant finances ~<strong>90bp</strong> tighter, at much higher gearing,
        than an uncontracted one on cash-flow certainty <em>alone</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        So the premium here is the <strong>~90bp certainty slice</strong> — not
        the ~225bp CoreWeave DDTL 4-vs-5 gap or the ~700bp IG-vs-non-IG gap,
        which bundle counterparty credit a hedge cannot repair. Those are
        carried only as upper bounds.
      </p>
      <p>
        No published cost-of-capital estimate exists for GPU infrastructure
        itself. We therefore use the closest peer-reviewed analogue — merchant
        versus contracted infrastructure project finance — while recognizing that
        the technology-risk profile of GPUs (a 2–3-year economic life and rapid
        obsolescence) could move the true premium in either direction.
      </p>

      <h2>The model</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Intensive margin</strong> (the headline): excess annual interest
        = exposed debt stock × certainty premium, where the exposed stock is the
        portion of GPU/AI-compute debt financed <em>without</em> cash-flow
        certainty — uncontracted, or contracted-but-not-bankable.
      </p>
      <p>
        The three inputs are deliberately different in kind. The debt stock is
        <strong>measured</strong> — the <a href="/credit">CCIR credit ledger</a>,
        not a model. The certainty premium is <strong>taken from peer-reviewed
        literature</strong>. Only the exposed fraction is <strong>modeled</strong>.
        That isolates the one soft input, which the next section builds up rather
        than asserts.
      </p>

      <div class="grid-wrap">
        <table class="data grid">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Scenario</th><th>Debt base</th><th>× Exposed</th><th>= Exposed $</th><th>× Premium</th><th>Excess / yr</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {scenarios.map((s) => (
              <tr class={s.name === 'Central' ? 'central' : ''}>
                <td class="nm">{s.name}</td><td>{s.base}</td><td>{s.frac}</td><td>{s.exposed}</td><td>{s.prem}</td><td class="num">{s.cost}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="headline">
        <strong>~$0.15–1.0 billion per year today, central case ≈ $0.4 billion.</strong>
        Roughly half of the ~$83B GPU-collateralized book is financed as though
        its cash flows were uncontracted; the ~90bp certainty slice would strip
        that spread out — about $0.4B a year at today's stock.
      </p>

      <h2>Building the exposed fraction</h2>
      <p>
        On a revenue basis the sector looks ~98% contracted — but
        <em>contracted ≠ bankable</em>. A dollar of debt is cash-flow-certain to
        a lender only if its revenue is contracted for the debt's life, from
        diversified and creditworthy counterparties, on a contract the lender can
        pledge. Rather than assert a single percentage, we build the exposed
        share up from the underwriting characteristics that break those
        conditions:
      </p>
      <div class="grid-wrap">
        <table class="data grid">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Underwriting gap</th><th>Why it exposes the cash flow</th><th>Book</th><th>From the ledger</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td class="nm">Merchant / uncontracted</td><td class="desc">No forward revenue to sell</td><td class="num">~5%</td><td class="desc grnd">reasoned</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="nm">Sub-IG counterparty</td><td class="desc">Locked revenue only as good as a weak or unrated payer</td><td class="num">~20%</td><td class="desc grnd">partly tagged</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="nm">Customer concentration</td><td class="desc">Diversification absent — one hyperscaler at 62–72% of revenue</td><td class="num">~15%</td><td class="desc grnd">measured (borrower)</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="nm">Tenor mismatch</td><td class="desc">Contract (2–5yr) shorter than debt (≥5yr); the tail years are merchant</td><td class="num">~15%</td><td class="desc grnd">measured (debt)</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="nm">Non-assignable contract</td><td class="desc">Offtake can't be pledged to the lender as collateral</td><td class="num">~10%</td><td class="desc grnd">reasoned</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        These gaps overlap heavily — a concentrated book is often also sub-IG; a
        mismatched contract is often also non-assignable — so the composite is a
        <strong>de-overlapped union, not the ~65% naive sum</strong>. It lands at
        roughly <strong>40–55%, central ~48%</strong>. The magnitudes are
        approximate; the point is that the figure <em>emerges from observable
        underwriting characteristics</em> rather than being asserted, and each is,
        in principle, measurable from the filings — the direction a future
        revision takes.
      </p>
      <p>
        Three of the five the ledger already constrains. <strong>Borrower
        concentration</strong> is measured and high — the top borrower is 36% of
        the GPU-collateralized book, the top three 56%, a Herfindahl near 1,700
        (the customer-side 62–72% figure comes from the borrowers' own filings).
        <strong>Debt tenor</strong> is measured — 79% of the dated book matures in
        four to six years, a median of ~5, which outlives the 2–5-year offtake
        contracts and the 2–3-year hardware. And ~<strong>22%</strong> of the book
        names an explicit non-IG or unrated offtaker in its filing (33% explicitly
        IG; the rest untagged) — a floor on the sub-IG share, not a ceiling.
        Merchant exposure and contract assignability the filings don't disclose
        systematically, so those two rows stay reasoned. Sharpening them is a
        data-collection task, not a modeling one.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is also why the estimate's width lives here and not in the premium:
        the premium (~90bp, peer-reviewed) moves the answer ~1.4×; the exposed
        fraction moves it ~7×. The residual opacity in these five inputs is
        precisely what a neutral reference would resolve.
      </p>

      <h2>Why "today" understates it</h2>
      <p>
        The cost scales with the debt stock, and the stock is early. Against
        Morgan Stanley's ~$1.5T data-center financing gap over 2025–28, the
        exposed-eligible book builds toward $500B–$1T. At 50% exposed × 90bp
        that is <strong>~$2–5 billion per year by 2028</strong> — on debt the
        sector is already committed to building.
      </p>

      <h2>The larger, conditional prize</h2>
      <p>
        The bigger channel is financing that never happens. Uncontracted
        structures size debt at ~50% advance and ~2× coverage — roughly half the
        debt per dollar of cash flow. A liquid hedge could
        <strong>materially increase debt capacity where revenue volatility is the
        binding underwriting constraint</strong>, substituting cheap debt for
        expensive equity. It is not a universal lever: lenders also size to
        collateral and residual value, sponsor strength, operational track record
        and covenants, and where one of those binds instead, a revenue hedge does
        less. And it is realized <strong>only if the benchmark is liquid,
        low-basis, and cleared</strong> — the freight-derivatives history is
        explicit that a reference without a clearing venue does not move financing
        terms. We keep it out of the headline.
      </p>

      <h2>Why it doesn't exist yet</h2>
      <p>
        If the benefit runs to billions a year, why hasn't a cleared
        compute-forward market already formed? The frictions are real, and they
        are the reason the market is unfinancialized rather than an oversight:
      </p>
      <ul class="caveats">
        <li><strong>Heterogeneous assets.</strong> An H100-hour, a GB200-hour and an A100-hour are different products; a tradable forward needs a standard deliverable, and the market has no agreed grade.</li>
        <li><strong>Basis risk.</strong> Any single reference differs from a given operator's realized price by chip, region, tenancy and interruptibility — the basis a hedger is left holding.</li>
        <li><strong>Technology cycles.</strong> A ~2–3-year hardware cadence caps the useful curve length and complicates long-dated contracts written against depreciating collateral.</li>
        <li><strong>No standardization.</strong> Contracts, SKUs and pricing units are bespoke per provider — there is no ISDA-equivalent for compute.</li>
        <li><strong>Few natural hedgers.</strong> Both sides of a forward — sellers of certainty and buyers of it — are still thin; most large demand is already contracted bilaterally.</li>
        <li><strong>Clearing economics.</strong> A cleared venue needs margin, default management and a settlement price no counterparty controls — which is exactly the neutral reference that does not yet exist.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Most of these are standardization and reference problems, not laws of
        nature — the same list, in power and in freight, was resolved by an agreed
        grade and a neutral settlement price.
      </p>

      <h2>Caveats</h2>
      <ul class="caveats">
        <li>Premium is the certainty slice only (~90bp); the 225/700bp spreads bundle counterparty credit and are upper bounds.</li>
        <li>The exposed fraction is a modeled scenario, not a measurement — the single largest source of range width, stated deliberately.</li>
        <li>Hedges are imperfect substitutes (basis, shape, volume risk persist); the certainty slice is narrowed, not closed.</li>
        <li>Value grows as the forward curve lengthens toward the ~5yr debt tenor; the extensive margin is conditional on a cleared venue.</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="method">
        Method: certainty-premium from
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.eneco.2022.106312" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Gohdes/Simshauser/Wilson
        (2022, <em>Energy Economics</em> v114)</a>; debt base from the
        <a href="/credit">CCIR credit ledger</a> (GPU-collateralized subset) and
        BIS / Morgan Stanley sizing; exposure framework from lender and
        rating-agency criteria. A CCIR working estimate — figures are ranges.
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>

  <style>
    .top { padding-top: 32px; }
    .page-head { max-width: 80ch; margin-bottom: 8px; }
    .page-head h1 {
      font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: var(--fs-3xl);
      line-height: var(--lh-display); font-weight: var(--weight-display);
      margin: 6px 0 12px;
    }
    .standfirst em { font-style: italic; color: var(--accent); }
    .standfirst a { color: var(--accent); }

    .body { max-width: 80ch; }
    .body h2 {
      font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: var(--fs-xl);
      margin: 28px 0 8px;
    }
    .body p {
      font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: var(--fs-md);
      color: var(--ink); line-height: 1.65; margin: 0 0 14px;
    }
    .body p em { color: var(--accent); font-style: italic; }
    .body a { color: var(--accent); }
    .headline {
      border-left: 2px solid var(--accent); padding: 4px 0 4px 16px;
      margin: 18px 0 !important; font-size: var(--fs-lg) !important;
    }
    .headline strong { color: var(--ink); }

    .grid-wrap { border: 1px solid var(--rule); background: var(--surface); overflow-x: auto; margin: 8px 0 18px; }
    table.grid { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-family: var(--font-mono); }
    table.grid th { text-align: right; font-size: var(--fs-xs); color: var(--ink-dim); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: var(--tracking-eye); }
    table.grid th:first-child, table.grid td.nm { text-align: left; }
    table.grid td.desc { text-align: left; color: var(--ink-dim); font-family: var(--font-body); }
    table.grid td.grnd { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--fs-xs); color: var(--ink-faint); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.04em; }
    table.grid td { text-align: right; font-size: var(--fs-sm); color: var(--ink); }
    table.grid tr.central { background: var(--surface-2); }
    table.grid tr.central td.nm { color: var(--accent); font-weight: var(--weight-strong); }
    table.grid td.num { color: var(--accent); font-weight: var(--weight-strong); }

    .caveats { max-width: 84ch; margin: 4px 0 18px; padding-left: 18px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
    .caveats li { font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: var(--fs-sm); color: var(--ink-dim); line-height: 1.55; }
    .method {
      font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--fs-xs) !important;
      color: var(--ink-faint) !important; line-height: 1.7 !important;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--rule); padding-top: 14px; margin-top: 24px !important; max-width: 90ch;
    }
    .method a { color: var(--accent); }
  </style>
</Base>
